HIV/AIDS: China reports increased 14% in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14% in the number of citizens living with HIV or AIDS.
According to health officials, more than 820,000 people in the country are affected.
In the second quarter of 2018, approximately 40,000 new cases were reported.
In contrast to the past, the transmission took place in the vast majority of the new cases through sexual intercourse.
So far, HIV rapidly spread in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people who have been infected with HIV in this way have been almost reduced to zero, Chinese health officials announced at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, in the year comparison, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 100,000 in China.
HIV transmission through sex is an acute problem in China’s LGBT community.
In 1997, homosexuality was decriminalised in China, but the discrimination of LGBT community members is to be widespread.
Due to the conservative values of the country, studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with men ultimately marry women.
Many of the disease transfers are due to inadequate protection during sexual intercourse in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government promises, among other things, general access to HIV drugs to address the problem.
