Update to the Red Tide: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota take off
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that a general decline in concentrations of red tide in parts of the Tampa Bay area has been recorded.
According to the FWC, in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts are recorded more exhaustive flowering conditions, indicating decreasing concentrations.
A red algae flower extends over approximately 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the Lee district.
Stains can be found about 10 miles off the Hillsborough district coast, but in less places compared to previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the district of Pasco.
Last week, mean concentrations in or off the coast of the district Pinellas have been reported, low to high concentrations in or off the coast of the district Manatee, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the district Charlotte, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the district Lee and low concentrations in the district Collier.
Respiratory complaints are still reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the northwest of Florida, no new respiratory problems have been known over the past week.
